You are an AI coding assistant working in a C# (Unity) codebase.

High-level goals
- Favor clarity over brevity. Code must read like English and be easy to explain to a junior colleague.
- Prefer simple, explicit constructs over cleverness.
- Do not refactor or restructure existing code unless explicitly requested. Make the smallest correct change.

Comments (strict)
- Do not add comments in code: no `//`, no `/* */`, no XML documentation (`///`), no `// TODO`, no region descriptions. The user does not write comments; mirror that unless the user explicitly asks for comments or documentation in code.

Output rules
- When generating code: output ONLY code (no explanations) unless the user explicitly asks for rationale.
- Do not add TODOs, placeholder code, or comments unless the user explicitly asks for comments.
- Preserve existing public APIs unless the user explicitly requests breaking changes.

Communication and token use (assistant behavior)
- Default to short, direct answers. Expand only when the user asks for depth, debugging help, or teaching.
- Prefer code citations and file paths over long prose. Do not repeat the same explanation in multiple phrasings.
- Do not list obvious next steps or filler closings unless the user asks.
- For simple tasks, skip long preambles and postambles.

C# language / syntax prohibitions
- NEVER use `var`. Always write explicit types.
- NEVER use `dynamic`.
- NEVER use target-typed `new()` (i.e., `new()` is forbidden). Always write `new TypeName(...)`.
- NEVER use `#region`.
- Avoid Reflection entirely. Do not use Reflection unless explicitly requested and no alternatives exist; if forced, cache results.

Braces / formatting
- Use Allman braces: every opening brace on its own line; always use braces even for single-line blocks.
- Keep line length reasonable. Consider wrapping past ~100 chars; must wrap by ~130 chars.
- When wrapping, keep operators on the original line and indent continuation lines by 4 spaces.

`using` directives
- Place `using` directives at the top of file.
- Group in this order: System, Unity, External, Company, Application.
- Sort alphabetically within each group.
- Separate groups with a single blank line (only when there are 3+ logical dependency groups).
- Place `using` alias directives AFTER all other usings at the bottom of the using section.
- Alias names must include a prefix that indicates the class/source (e.g., SystemRandom, UnityRandom).

Ordering within types
- Order members in this exact sequence:
  1) Constant fields
  2) Fields
  3) Constructors
  4) Finalizers (destructors)
  5) Delegates
  6) Events
  7) Properties
  8) Indexers
  9) Methods
- Within each group order by access:
  public, internal, protected internal, protected, private
- For fields, within each access group order:
  [SerializeField] first, then non-[SerializeField]
  then static, then non-static
  then readonly, then non-readonly
- Nested types must be at the very top of the containing type, ordered:
  Enums, Interfaces, Structs, Classes
- Modifiers order must be:
  public protected internal private new abstract virtual override sealed static readonly extern unsafe volatile async
  Always specify visibility explicitly (even when default).

Naming conventions (Visual Studio defaults)
- Public types/members/properties/methods: PascalCase.
- Method names (incl. local functions): PascalCase, verb or verb phrase.
- Private/internal instance fields: `_camelCase`.
- Private/internal static fields: `s_camelCase`.
- Thread static fields: `t_camelCase`.
- Method parameters and local variables: camelCase.
- Interfaces: start with `I` (e.g., IWorkerQueue).
- Attribute types: end with `Attribute`.
- EventArgs types: end with `EventArgs`.
- Exceptions: end with `Exception`.
- Enums: singular for non-flags; plural for flags. Do NOT suffix enums with Enum/Flag/Flags.
- Do NOT use Hungarian notation or type-prefixes in variable names.
- Avoid abbreviations and contractions unless they are widely accepted and truly necessary.
- Prefer clarity over brevity; choose descriptive names.
- Do not use two consecutive underscores in identifiers.

Semantics / design constraints
- Use named constants instead of magic numbers. Prefer `const`; if not possible, prefer `readonly`.
- Do not do heavy operations inside properties.
- Do not mutate object state in check/get methods (e.g., `CanX`, `IsX`, `TryX`, getters).
- Do not throw exceptions in check methods.
- Do not `return` or `throw` from inside loops. If early exit is needed, move the search/validation into a separate method and use `break` to exit loops.
- Prefer splitting complex preconditions into a dedicated method (e.g., `CanStartGame()`).

Nullable rules
- For Nullable<T>, prefer explicit initialization (e.g., `int? score = new int?();`).
- Prefer `.HasValue` / `.Value` patterns over `== null` / `!= null` comparisons for Nullable<T>.

LINQ rules (Unity)
- Do NOT use LINQ in runtime/production code (allocations/readability). Editor-only code may use LINQ.

Unity scene lookup (strict)
- Do NOT use `FindObjectOfType`, `FindObjectsOfType`, `FindFirstObjectByType`, `FindObjectsByType`, or `Object.FindAnyObjectByType` to resolve references at runtime. Wire dependencies via serialized fields, constructor/`Init` parameters from a composition root, or DIâ€”never by searching the scene.

Extension methods
- Add extension methods only if you cannot modify the source type or itâ€™s not feasible.
- Only for core/general functionality and only in core libraries available everywhere.

Try/catch rules
- Prefer try/catch/finally to cover the whole method. If only part needs protection, extract that part into its own method.
- Do NOT name exception variables `e` (reserved for EventArgs). Use `ex`.

Attributes
- Each attribute must be on its own line. Do not combine attributes on one line.

Events
- Prefer `EventHandler` over `Action` for events.
- Event names should NOT start with `On`. Use verbs and tense appropriately (e.g., Closing/Closed).
- If an event name conflicts with a method name, prefix the invoking method with `Perform` (e.g., event `Click`, method `PerformClick`).
- Event handler method naming: `On<fieldOrVarName><EventName>` (e.g., `_homeButton.Click += OnHomeButtonClick;`).
- Always unsubscribe from events when appropriate to avoid leaks.

Unity serialization
- Remember Unity does not serialize `readonly` fields.
- When inheriting and serializing fields, use `[Header("...")]` to clarify ownership/section in the Inspector.

MVP UI windows (single structure)
- New full-screen or modal UI â€świndowsâ€ť that participate in the app shell must follow one pattern: inherit `DroneSimulator.Presentation.UI.Window` or `Window<TPresenter>`; implement `WindowType`; register the presenter in DI and resolve it in `InitPresenter`.
- Add a new member to `WindowType` when adding a managed window.
- Structure: `WindowType` property â†’ `OnShow` / `OnHide` for visibility and subscriptions â†’ UI bindings only in the view; logic in the presenter (or existing domain services injected via DI). Do not duplicate this pattern with ad-hoc `MonoBehaviour` windows for the same layer unless the user explicitly asks for an exception.
- The presenter is always obtained when the window is initialized through `UIManager` (`Init` â†’ `InitPresenter` â†’ resolve from DI). Do not add alternate initialization paths (e.g. standalone/fallback presenters, scene lookups, or lazy self-wiring in `Start`/`Awake`).

Git (see docs/git-conventions.md)
- When suggesting commit messages, branch names, or Git workflow steps, follow `docs/git-conventions.md`.
